ting Tips","public_url":"https://eartheasy.local/articles/bird-safe-painting-tips/","featured_image":"https://eartheasy.local/site-files/2018/01/sultan-k-75533.jpg","additional_images":["https://eartheasy.local/site-files/2018/01/sultan-k-75533.jpg","https://eartheasy.local/site-files/2018/01/hermes-rivera-226686.jpg"],"post_date":"2009-01-09 18:53:55","post_category":"Health &amp; Wellness","post_type":"ee_articles","post_id":10014,"post_description":"Pet birds can be hard on cages, often chewing, scratching or wearing the paint. They can ingest flakes of paint which can be harmful to their health. Pet birds can also be sensitive to fumes from new paint."},{"title":"Healthy Lawns, Healthy Lungs?","public_url":"https://eartheasy.local/articles/healthy-lawns-healthy-lungs/","featured_image":"https://eartheasy.local/site-files/2017/11/phil-goodwin-96377-web.jpg","additional_images":["https://eartheasy.local/site-files/2017/11/phil-goodwin-96377-web.jpg","https://eartheasy.local/site-files/2017/11/jonas-weckschmied-117633-web.jpg","https://eartheasy.local/site-files/2017/11/paul-303767-web.jpg"],"post_date":"2009-01-05 20:57:12","post_category":"Health &amp; Wellness","post_type":"ee_articles","post_id":6619,"post_description":"Now that spring is in the air, the fancy of many home owners turns to lawn care. But this annual ritual doesn't bring much joy to Dr. June Irwin, one of the most outspoken members of the Canadian medical profession on the subject of pesticides in urban areas."},{"title":"Last Child in the Woods","public_url":"https://eartheasy.local/articles/last-child-in-the-woods/","featured_image":"https://eartheasy.local/site-files/2017/11/annie-spratt-37789-web.jpg","additional_images":["https://eartheasy.local/site-files/2017/11/annie-spratt-37789-web.jpg","https://eartheasy.local/site-files/2017/11/caroline-hernandez-315551-web.jpg"],"post_date":"2009-01-04 21:18:02","post_category":"Health &amp; Wellness","post_type":"ee_articles","post_id":6639,"post_description":"Children are spending less time outside than ever before. In this groundbreaking book, child advocate Richard Louv examines the implications of nature-free childhoods and what they mean for the future of our children and humanity."}]